The course revises basic folkloristic concepts, gives an overview of different folklore genres (incl. fairy tale, legend, folk song) and demonstrates how folklore texts can be analysed as well as used for practicing different skills. In addition, the course explores folk religion, customs and various other non-textual traditional phenomena as well as cultural diversity in Estonian context.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course familiarises students with approaches in contemporary folklore studies and with possibilities for teaching folklore in school. By means of seminars, readings and practical exercises, students acquire knowledge and skills for creating exercises on folklore topics, for supervising research papers on folklore related topics and for integrating different subjects by means of folklore.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon completing the course, students have an overview of theoretical and methodological tenets of contemporary folkloristics and are capable of applying them in teaching. Students know how to create exercises using folklore texts and how to conduct and supervise qualitative research projects on folkloristic topics that increase pupils' awareness of folklore's role in daily life and of their own role as bearers of various traditions. Participants are capable of using folklore to enhance oral and written self-expression skills, to develop critical thinking as well as to integrate various subjects.
